<div class="blurb">
<div class="header"><h1>Summary of 'Glutamate Storms' (Excitotoxicity) (20260107)</h1></div>
<div class="body">
<ol>
  <li>
    <strong>Definition & Function of Glutamate</strong>
    <p>Glutamate is the central nervous system's primary excitatory neurotransmitter, essential for normal brain functions.</p>
    <ol type="a">
      <li>Key functions include learning, memory, energy production, and neural communication.</li>
      <li>Normal levels are maintained by an efficient reuptake system involving astrocytes and neurons.</li>
      <li>In a healthy state, it is released in small, controlled amounts into the synaptic cleft.</li>
    </ol>
  </li>
  <li>
    <strong>Mechanism of a 'Glutamate Storm'</strong>
    <p>This pathological cascade is generally a secondary injury response to acute trauma.</p>
    <ol type="a">
      <li>Initial injury (e.g., trauma, stroke) damages neurons and glia, causing them to release their large internal stores of glutamate all at once into the extracellular space.</li>
      <li>The reuptake systems fail due to energy depletion (lack of ATP) or physical damage, allowing glutamate to accumulate to toxic levels.</li>
      <li>Excess glutamate over-activates glutamate receptors (especially NMDA and AMPA receptors) on adjacent healthy neurons.</li>
      <li>This over-activation leads to an excessive influx of calcium ions into the cells.</li>
    </ol>
  </li>
  <li>
    <strong>Consequences and Cell Death</strong>
    <p>The influx of calcium triggers a series of destructive intracellular events.</p>
    <ol type="a">
      <li>Intracellular calcium overload disrupts mitochondrial function and energy production.</li>
      <li>Harmful enzymes (like proteases and lipases) and reactive oxygen species (free radicals) are produced, causing oxidative stress and inflammation.</li>
      <li>This leads to widespread damage and various forms of neuronal death, including apoptosis and necrosis.</li>
      <li>As these new cells die, they release their own glutamate stores, perpetuating the "storm" and creating a cascading effect of damage that radiates outward from the initial injury site.</li>
    </ol>
  </li>
  <li>
    <strong>Associated Conditions & Symptoms</strong>
    <p>Excitotoxicity is linked to various acute and chronic neurological conditions.</p>
    <ol type="a">
      <li>Acute conditions: Traumatic brain injury (TBI), stroke, cerebral ischemia, and prolonged seizures/epilepsy.</li>
      <li>Neurodegenerative diseases: Alzheimer's, Parkinson's, Huntington's, and amyotrophic lateral sclerosis (ALS).</li>
      <li>Common symptoms: Severe headaches, memory loss, confusion, anxiety, seizures, motor dysfunction, and in severe cases, coma and death.</li>
    </ol>
  </li>
</ol>
